- The Bridge Pattern is a structural design pattern that separates an abstraction from its 
implementation so that both can vary independently.
The Bridge Pattern splits a class into two independent hierarchies (abstraction and implementation) 
and connects them using composition instead of inheritance.
- To avoid class explosion, we used bridge pattern.


[ !Why do we need the Bridge Pattern? ]

- Suppose you're building a Remote Control System.

You have two types of remotes:
    Basic Remote
    Advanced Remote

And two types of TVs:
    Sony TV
    Samsung TV

If you use inheritance only:
             Remote
        /                   \
 BasicRemote          AdvancedRemote

        ×                     ×

     SonyTV             SamsungTV

You end up creating:
    BasicSonyRemote
    BasicSamsungRemote
    AdvancedSonyRemote
    AdvancedSamsungRemote

Today there are 4 classes.

Tomorrow you add LG TV Now, 
    BasicLGRemote
    AdvancedLGRemote

Tomorrow add VoiceRemote Now,
    VoiceSonyRemote
    VoiceSamsungRemote
    VoiceLGRemote

The number of classes keeps increasing. This is called the Class Explosion Problem.

Solution:
Instead of inheritance, connect them using composition.
    Remote
      |
      | has-a
      ▼
     TV

Now both can change independently.